text: Quite an interesting place to understand the history of English Banking System

Lots to see and learn despite its rather small size. There’s a gold bar on display that you can try to lift- it’s heavy! Would come here again. The souvenirs could use some re-designing, would like to buy sth with Bank of England print, but the styles are just too blend.
Really interesting insight into banking.
What can I say, great little museum. We are so lucky to have so much history. Free to go in which is brilliant. Well worth a visit.
Fascinating.

A good museum behind the bank of England. But it is a little bit small compared to some. But never the less it is still a good place to take the kids or learn history about money. Also there is a shop wear you can buy souvenirs.
It is a very interesting museum, and you can lift the gold bar on display Lots of information
Really interesting. Amazing considering its free. Just note it isn't open on weekends or Bank holidays
So interesting and Amazing!
Free Museum. We enjoyed our visit, including the Easter egg trail and activity
A small "financial" museum with a few noteworthy exhibits.
Very good tour, lots to see even held a bar of gold couldn't take it home tho
The pace does show quite a lot about the bank, coins and notes, but they roved one of the best parts which was a safe you could break into and get a pin from them.
Recommend paying a visit to this hidden gem! Free to visit, interesting information with a good level of depth for a casual visit.
It’s free and small but educational museum.
Lots info about the foundation of the banking system and about money; I was expecting more glimpses in the actual bank and vault.
Good museum detailing the history of money, printing of bills, electronic payments and lots more. The Future of Money exhibition provides a view of the not-distant future of monetary transactions.

An immersive journey through the history of money and the significance of central London in global finance awaits you. Don't miss the highlight: lifting a real gold bar with your own hands to feel its weight firsthand.
Lots of information on the bank going back to the beginning. Spend an hour or 2 browsing. Free
Fascinating museum visit
Could be improved especially modern economy section

Good displays. Clean. Understandable. A gold bar is very heavy... (try). Great interaction. Shame the assistants are not knowledgable about the actual bank. They only know about the displays. Must visit and it is FREE.
Tremendous place and nice area
Love the gold bar

Very interesting and certainly worth a visit. The staff are very helpful and there is a wealth of historic information. It was fascinating to be able to hold and feel the weight of a gold bar worth the guts of £800,000. Needless to say it is very secure but an awesome exhibit.
Great museum as well as an institution

It's ons of the places on my places to visit list It opens at 10 am & Closes at 5pm Free to get in nearest tube is Bank, which has many station exits The Barthomley Street Inside its amazing place to see its good for all kids ages from 8 till 16 and us oldies lol It's a fun place but gets a crowd after 1045 as the school children plus tourists arrive Check out this place theirs a gold bar in a box where you can try to lift it up. That's fun. I found You also get to see the new King Charles 🤴 notes & Coins. This place explains the history of how the bank was formed & many more interesting facts, which both kids & parents can have generally fun This is only open Monday till Friday only closed over the weekend check Bank of England's website
A very interesting place to visit. A nice place for an hour or two. Informative for all ages basically. Try picking up the Gold bar.
Excellent. Shame the shop didn't have any fridge magnets though 🙂
Small but very informative museum with free WiFi and a free audio guide accessible via QR code (thankfully not an app, it’s just a website). It’s a great way to spend an hour of your time.
Very interesting and good to know the history

Great museum and free entry. It presents the whole history of the Bank of England, all the different buildings on the site, and how its purpose progressed. It also describes the history of money from the 1600s to present day, the security features on the notes is very interesting. There's a gold bar in a display case that you can try to lift!
Interesting museum
Excellent free museum, much more to see than you might expect
It was so interesting to visit and it's free to go to.
Great Conference in a great building; infusing history, elegance, modernisation...
Get to know about money

Excellent free Museum. It's very well explained and very well illustrated. You can even lift a real gold bar. It covers the history of before the Bank existed to crypto currencies.There's a couple of things on slavery etc but its not as preachy as some museums.
Awesome experience.
A small exhibition, but interesting.
Worth visiting if you've got an hour to kill for sure. Some interesting info in there.
An interesting place, I particularly liked holding the gold bar.
Very interesting - sadly no free samples😁

The Bank of England Museum is an excellent and informative museum where you can learn about money, the UK economy, and the history of this significant institution. The museum boasts an impressive collection of 40,000 items, including a real gold bar that visitors can try to lift up. Please note that the museum is closed on bank holidays and weekends. However, it is open to the public free of charge.

Went on a half-term visit with a younger family member. There were useful facts on display visually and in print. Some of the games, like trying to balance inflation, stirred the imagination. Also, how the bank and some of it's staff were involved in the slave trade was revealing. Some good takeaways.
Great visit and excellent presentation to our group.
The information about slavery is deep and helpful

The Bank of England Museum is a hidden gem in London, perfect for families interested in history, economics, and interactive learning. The free entry, engaging exhibits, and educational value make it a must-visit for anyone exploring the city.
Pretty good stands but Is quite confusing for people who don't already know things about it
Great museum with nice displays about the history of the bank in UK
Little bit dated museum with a good story
It was interesting place

A dive into the history of the Bank of England with a wealth of fascinating information! The secrets of making banknotes and the weight of a gold bar (to lift yourself) are also very interesting. The whole, however, perhaps lacks a little economic and financial popularization.
Great visit, free and very informativ. A lot of interactive material accessible for all!
Kindness
Good museum adjacent to Bank. Good displays about the history of banking and the bank itself. Well worth a visit - if only to try lifting a gold bar! Security was a but slow.

Very interesting museum about the Bank of England with some interactive games for children and some curious objects, including a gold longote that you can touch (it doesn't give you super powers or make you rich) if you pass by there it's not bad to spend half a day on it. hour or hour, it's free so you don't lose anything by going to see it.
Amazing museum. Great experience in holding a real Gold Bar! Must visit place..
Really great museum, very interesting! Awesome to be able to hold and feel the weight of an actual bar of gold.
Had nice time here. It seems they also organise some theme bank games for children
very good event for Christmas.
It was interesting, unfortunately not possible in German. I would have thought it would be bigger too
Interesting Museum which lets you know about the history of the bank as well as currencies. Most Preserved one and best knowledge for educational purposes.
Fascinating visit, I loved learning about the origins of money
Very interesting museum. Some exhibitions not well laid out. Slavery and bank history were quite confused.

A great museum! No charge to enter and some amazing displays! You can (try)to lift a real gold bar! A lot of interesting information on the economy, bank ( and) other notes, coins, currency, the economy and more. In a great location in the city. A nice shop with some cool souvenirs.
A Small part of the bank set up as a museum about banking in the UK and parts of the world.
Fabulous experience, we arrived at 4 pm and got in bye 5pm. Very proud to own my Bauble Free mince pies and Mulled wine and Carol singing ❤ London
Excellent historical museum to visit. Kids also enjoyed learning about the history and operation of the bank. Free to enter. Can be enjoyed within 90 minutes.
Too busy we couldn't get into the Carol Concert and the baubles were all gone. We will visit at a quieter time.

We visited with young adults (Economics students) and I felt that this could've been so much more than it was. There's such a big story behind the bank and whilst the museum is enjoyable, it just doesn't do the story justice. The slavery exhibition was okay. I felt it could be something more than what it was. It felt cold and clinical. I wanted to see more of the human side of things, and more suggestions on how we reconcile this part of our history. If you can add this to your trip to London, then do. It takes about 45 minutes to an hour and would be perfect for 10+ year olds. Make sure you scan the code for the audio tour, this will add extra depth to your tour.
Interesting museum and economics and the history behind the National Bank of England. Free entry.
Perfect and intereating place for both children and adults.
Robbers
Quite interesting story of British currency. Entry is free.
Great couple of hrs spent here. Very interesting.
Loads of interactive games and a fun visit. Also attended a lecture which was really informative. You get to see and pick up a real gold bar and indulge in interactive inflation and money simulators

Lovely small (an hour or so) museum looking at what the bank is, how it came to be, and the history of our money. It's a delightful tour, especially for numismatists. Entry is completely free. The staff are helpful, answering questions we had. Definitely recommend.
Good place to spend some time

Took my niece to have a look round and she found a challenging safe to open .unfortunately she could not open it but she asked the lady behind the counter who showed her how to do it .just wish to say she was amazing and made my nieces day with a picture of gold bars all the staff are so polite. We'll worth a visit .thanks from both of us.
Very interesting and quick to see, don't hesitate to go there, the entrance is free, there is just a search and no waiting.

The museum turned out to be unexpectedly more interesting than initially expected. The museum is small and tells about the emergence of money, banks, how the slave trade and the import of sugar and tea influenced the banking and financial system. You can touch and try to lift a gold bar weighing 13 kg! Lots of different interactive activities for children. The entrance is free!

Great exhibition about the Bank of England, it has all the old bank notes. A story of the history of money and cheques. It has a gold bar that you can lift it to see how heavy it is. It also has a photo of gold bars on the wall when you can have a selfie in front of. When you go in this is the bar where people used to go to pay their money in, when it first opened. It has a shop where you can buy keyrings of goldbars and little teddy's with Bank of England on them. They have toilets inside. It's good for children to learn all about the Bank of England. The staff are very friendly and helpful and very knowledgeable about the museum.

A small, friendly, pleasant and free museum in the heart of London's banking district. The welcome is warm, the layout sober but interesting. Games in the first room welcome children (including a chest with an old lock to open). The room which shows how banknotes are made is fascinating. And the highlight of the visit: you can try to lift a real gold ingot (well protected in a display case, all the same!) To visit with children and even without.

Must see! It's not popular, there aren't many people. Entry is free, after a quick security check, with time travel and interactive elements. If you want to hold a 15-kilo gold bar, want to know what the karat is, which is the unit of measure, want to see war photos or sit on a chest of 20 pounds, don't miss it. We really liked it, the ràadàs was a concert by a string quartet!
This museum is a hidden treasure. It's free, fascinating and worth testing your arm strength by trying to lift a gold bar.
A very nice museum, where you can understand the banknote process and also touch a gold bar, a great experience.
Great exhibition on slavery and banking. Really informative.

Visited at lunchtime on the day of the Lord Mayor's show, (Not usually open on a weekend apparently). Interesting displays and a chance to hold a Gold bar, lots of information about Money. There was face painting for the kids and a worksheet for them to complete. Entry was free.
Exceeded my expectations. I learnt a lot. The building is very grand and impressive too. The staff were nice
Lots of interesting information presented to appeal to all ages. The opportunity to handle (and lift!) real gold bar was truly memorable.
Wonderful free museum. Lots of interesting information and exhibits

Enjoyed the experience more than expected. An impressive entrance and welcoming staff. Bag search only to be expected but carried out efficiently and courteously. The origins and growth of the Bank of England is imaginatively displayed with fascinating insights into its architect( Sir John Soane)and the many financial vicissitudes as the bank grew and evolved. The section detailing with the development of bank notes together with the many different designs, dimensions and anti forgery ploys were all beautifully explained. The visit lasted about two hours and we left determined to revisit and with plans to spend more time with specific displays. Toilets were immaculate and the gift shop well stocked with inexpensive souvenirs as well as more valuable items. All good.
Really interesting museum in the heart of the city. Spent much more time there during the visit than we thought we would!

Bank of England 1823 - (best example of Greek revival in England) its original city plan was irrational in medieval style, so when it got burnt, John Soane revived it with a more classical/ orderly city plan
Small museum. Interesting. Done in 30 mins
Fascinating. I spent hours. Free. Real innovations in finance. Honest reflections in special Slave trade exhibition

The museum being free is definitely a point of interest as I feel charging for entry would be a step too far. The reason being is that it's a very brief, albeit interesting insight on the storied history of the Bank of England that stretches right up to the modern day. It's fascinating to understand how the cycle of the world renowned Pound comes into being and also the many creative ways fraudsters try to dole out fake notes and even more fascinating is the video detailing how the notes go from concept to design to circulation right into the tax man's pocket. If you've got a spare half hour going and you're in the area, then give the place a whirl - it is free, after all.
Thank-you it was both informative and participative. And thanks for the friendly welcome.
Small museum but interesting nonetheless.
To do
Interesting exhibits about the Bank of England
Lots of history and knowledge in one place.
Lifting the gold bar is just great.
Small and disappointing.
Very interesting museum showing how the bank started and its colourful history! Go just to get your hands on the gold bar and see the £1 million pound note
First off, entry is free. Very interesting with activities to keep the younger ones occupied.

NICE FREE ATTRACTION IN LONDON! I was pleasantly surprised with the Bank of England Museum, it’s an interesting look at how the concept of money was formed and that most of what modern banking is (loans, interest, bank notes) were invented right here. You’ll get to learn all about money, how money is made, how counterfeiters forge bank notes and you can even lift a bar of real gold (an 11kg London Good Bar with an approximate value of £700,000). The fact that it’s free is a massive bonus. So if you’re passing by and you have a spare 30 minutes, it’s definitely worth going inside!
Excellent and fascinating museum. Stayed 45minutes could have stayed longer but had to leave. Will definitely go again. Free entry.
A good well curated museum, interesting and informative displays. Pleasant staff and security.
Very interesting
Not easy to find. Nice staff but very disappointed by the content of the museum.

I enjoyed my visited here. It was very interesting and informative to learn about the banks history and slavery. We were greeted at the entrance by a security guard! - Wasn't expecting that! - It goes to show how this place is of upmost high importance! After going through the doors you will have your bags checked by security! It was like being at a airport as we went through the security doors to check if we had any dangerous weapons! Haha! As if! Afterwards, you will be greeted by the receptionist and be given a map of the museum. It was not very busy on the late afternoon but there were a group of school kids (that packed out an area we were in.) Clean toilets but small. Small and intimate museum I thought. We spent about an hour or so looking around. Lots of information to read and a little screen to watch about its history. There was a very very small gift shop area which was very expensive! However, we did purchase a magnet for £5. Crazy price! Cashier was friendly and social! I loved the ceilings and lighting! Amazing work to look up at! Overall, a good day out! Definitely recommend visiting!
A lovely small museum detailing the history of the Bank of England. There is no charge so well worth popping in if you're in the City
Good history of money and the slave trade
Nice visit Free museum
Only popped in to waste a few minutes before our train, but as a free-to-access museum it was very interesting and it's not every day that you get to hold a real bar of gold!
This museum is a real treasure! The exhibits are impressive, and I had a fantastic experience.
Pleasure to visit. Interesting for both adults and children. Gave insights into how banking as we know it came to be.
A very educated trip and it was free.

Fascinating (free) museum located within the BoE. Learn about the bank’s history, how banknotes are designed and visit the vaults. Have a go at lifting a gold bar are some of the fun things you can do at this cool museum!

Interesting museum sadly, I could not make any deposits at the bank. Really interesting. Display in the museum, which included a gold bar. The sort of bullion that you see in these films. Not only that, you could lift it up. Obviously it is in a cage, no not me, the bullion, so you cant walk out with it. Not sure why, as they claim to have many in the vaults, so just one for me would probably not be missed! Certainly worth a visit. AND ENTRY IS FREE. Bullion is extra.
Excellent displays and information. Worth visiting
Incredible museum! The exhibits are breathtaking. I had an amazing time here

Super cool museum in London. It's an absolute shame that it's not open on weekends. Secret Tip : The museum is open until 8 pm on the third Thursday of every month. Do check out the interactive games such as Economic Shock, Locker Challenge and last but not the least, lifting the gold bar. I felt they could do lot more guided tours during the day and open atleast on one of the weekends in a month/quarter.

It is an interesting experience and becoming aware of where everything comes from. Even the Netherlands, and in particular the Bank of Amsterdam, was an important example for the Bank of England in the past. You can even touch a gold bar weighing 13kg and 99.7% pure gold.
Nice

Surprised how interesting this was and how well presented. And it was FREE! Of particular note was their exhibition regarding the Bank's association with the Slave Trade. Ran out of time but would return for a longer visit.
Amazing!
Very interesting, not for young children
A small but interesting museum - walkable in about an hour. Unfortunately, some interactive attractions were closed. You can hold a large gold bar :)
Really great place to visit. Interesting building, good informative exhibits. Make sure you lift the gold bar!!
Not very popular, but a really interesting free museum. I recommend it to everyone!
Small museum, worth a visit if you are nearby. Loved seeing and being able to lift a real gold bar! Wished the gift shop had more variety.
FTMO, thank you.
Very interesting to explore its history, and the route is not very long.
Good in-depth history of the bank as you would expect. It's free so that's a bonus!
A bit boring
Very interesting place to visit.
Lovely little Museum about the history of the bank.
Very nice feeling.
Nice place to learn about how money is made. My children and I were very happy to be able to see and touch actual gold bar and to be able to lift one. It was overall a very nice experience.
Nice little museum that shows the development of the banking system.
Interesting but very small

Interesting museum in and of itself, if a bit “dated”; Children were very happy to have cracked the "safe" in no time, but very disappointing was the extremely puny present that was disproportionate to the performance: a cheap postcard with self-promotion! Estimated value, 8-10 pence. That's really how you motivate!

A lovely little look into the world of the bank of England, insightful and harrowing to see the slave trade starting this, nice that they have put all the names up to honour them. We won the puzzle reward too which was good fun.

I went for the exhibition on slavery: it was good and it is important that it is there. But I would have liked to see more details, more results of in depth reseach. I'm sure they tjey have the money for it...
History's of Bank and old currency
A very original and interesting place, hiding many stories about how money was created over the centuries.

We had booked a guided tour. It was quite crowded inside but very informative. The displays were well laid out and informative. It's mainly for elderly children and adults as children may find it a bit boring
Good little museum for the little ones
Nice little walk around
Steps to get into with heavy doors.
Surprisingly large and interesting free museum! Def worth a visit!
Really cool museum,, not ginormous so you have enough time to really appreciate everything and it’s well set up! The gold bar is also pretty cool!
Interesting little museum with some child friendly activities. It's not very accessible for visiting with a pram, there are four sets of 3/4 steps throughout the visit.
Essential visit
Small museum, but they have a lot of information about slavery. And it has security.
Some interesting displays and exhibits. Didn't see any guides to give you information or to whom you could ask questions. Something for older generations I believe, not children

I visited The Bank of England Museum, in London, United Kingdom, in October 2022, because i am, great at and love finance. I found the security guards and museum staff were very friendly and polite. The building was massive on the outside but small and easy to get around on the inside. I bought a few gold bullion chocolate bars, a gold bullion key ring and a beautiful leather Bank of England black notebook. I highly recomend The Bank of England Museum Thankyou
A nice little museum in the heart of Liverpool Street. Approx a hours visit. Toilets on site. Small gift shop. Worth a visit if you have a hour to spare and then enjoy some sightseeing around London.
Good specialized museum
Nice place to visit lot of things to see free entry to all rooms. Enjoyed seeing all the timelines and the story boards.

Disappointing. Rather old fashioned style museum . Would have expected something more state of the art from BoE. The gold bar is the most interesting and interactive artefact. Still it is nice to be able to enter the BoE building
Some of this is very interesting, however some of it is dull
Very lovely little museum.

A fine and little museum. With a lot to learn about economic and the history of the United kingdom. So there was the special exibition about slavery and the bank. You can hold a 26 pound (13 kilo) heavy goldbar in one hand. Worth over 730000 Euro it Was heavy to lift with one hand.
Small, free and nice. Best bit is the gold bar.

Interesting museum, well documented. A part on slavery and the enrichment of England. One on the history of the building. Another on the making of money, anecdotes, an ingot to weigh, a little about the new currencies, puzzles to occupy the children in the first room and a small shop. Free museum, interesting visit.
be sure to visit this museum 😊❤
It's a small museum but it's free to enter and interesting.
Small but educational museum where you get a chance to hold a gold brick. Good enough for a free museum.
Free to enter open on week days until 5pm. If you want to learn history of monetary system and currency than this is a best place for you to visit. You can see and feel the 13k gold bar.
Quite disappointing. Expected to learn more about the banks activities. It was mostly about their building and any links it had to slavery.
A small but very interesting and free museum.

For a free museum it’s really not a bad place at all. Lots of little exhibits to look around and a fascinating history of how the Bank of England came to be. Gift shop here as well which is always a bonus for me.
As someone with a background in economics this was just a fun and free small stop for me. There is enough to keep the kids occupied and some deep history for the adults.
Decent but a bit repetitive
Meh. Don't have high expectations and you'll enjoy it. There was no line and it wasn't busy inside.
Great resource for economics students and the curious.
Was cool to learn about early economic bubbles and the bank’s history. Bottom left in the photo is one of world’s first coins.

Very interesting museum with free access which retraces the birth of the English bank, of banknotes, of the various types of paper and printing, of the different series of pounds... all displayed in an intelligent manner and with the usual Anglo-Saxon clarity of exposition. To visit.

In all my years of living and working in the city, I never knew there was a museum attached to the Bank of England. This is a great place to learn more about its origins and of course money. There was an exhibition on regarding the Slave Trade during those times and who profited from this. Took my little one (aged 6) who also found it fascinating. He was asked if he wanted to do an activity which he was most pleased about and kept him entertained whilst wandering around. I'm going back so I can take my time and actually read more instead of rush from one area to another 🤣
It is worth visiting and it is free.
Must visit when in london... learn about the role of bank of england and slavery acknowledgement.
A smaller museum, but great for a short pop in. The exhibit on security features was especially interesting
It's fine, probs wouldn't recommend
Important place you can learn about history of money.

It was pretty cool. The museum is free to visit, and has friendly and knowledgeable staff. It offers a fascinating insight into the history and role of the Bank of England, from its foundation in 1694 to the present day. The museum has a variety of exhibits and displays, covering topics such as monetary and financial stability, banknotes and coins, gold vaults, and transatlantic slavery.
Small but interesting museum. Free entrance
The museum was ok, but I wasn't impressed. Free entry
It's free and you can touch a gold bar! Also if you open a safe they give you a little something 😉
It is great for a free entry museum. It is things that you will expect from a free entry and bank related museum.
Interesting to learn about the history of the entity.

Interesting free museum with a couple of options to keep young visitors entertained (either drawing or hunting for clues) resulting in a nice "gold" ingot pin and a few interactive exibits. Good for a couple of hours. Wheelchair accessible. Closed at weekend and bank holidays.
Quite interesting half an hour or so.
Great learning experience
Surprisingly good content - interesting to learn about the bank's role in the slave trade and got to lift a gold bar. Did only take ah hour to get around, but it's free.

Another one of John Soane's works, the museum aspect of the bank is surprisingly in-depth with a detailed history and numerous artifacts as well as acknowledging the complicated history regarding slavery with its own exhibit space.
Very interesting place, artefacts and interesting talks - all free. Plus held a pure gold bar!
Small museum
Lovely staff, very informative, lots to see
We've won the prize - the original Bank of England pens !!! Hurray!!!!
It's free and has a vast collection of Coins and Banknotes and also has a printing machines so whoever interested to print the money then 'come to BOE'🤣
Really nice museum to learn about English banknotes
Worth a trip

Was on my disability scooter. Amazing 'magic steps' entry from street. Really nice inside the place, marble etc. Two talks were very interesting. Enjoyed my visit and will return to see more of museum.

Very interesting, I have learnt that there is far more to the Bank of England than one might think. With lots of interesting stories, and some good interactive exhibits this museum is a great place to visit for adults or teenagers interested in history or politics or monetary systems.
A free museum but with very little to see. I was disappointed. Ours in Lisbon is much more interesting.

Really interesting, enjoyable and even fun when you try to lift the heavy gold bar or sit on a pallet of banknotes. Banknotes and coins from the past on display, history, machinery and curiosities in a well-structured itinerary that is certainly pleasantly enjoyable even for children and teenagers. Obviously free!
Lovely,small,informative& "cozy" museum ,all about the money & bank of England.
Free, interesting, and varied. I'd take any child aged 8 and above.
At the moment it is free which is great. Learned a lot
Interesting and informative museum although fairly small so don't plan it as a whole-day activity
Good gold
Nice little museum, which finished our day to London of wonderfully, doesn't take long to go around, so we'll worth popping in.
Very interesting museum, the highlight is certainly the gold ingot that can be lifted
Brilliant... Everyone needs to go here... And it's free

Great except for the bit at the end where they ask kids how slavery makes them feel etc. broke my heart to see things like ‘ashamed’ or ‘guilty’ in children’s handwriting. I knew it would be silly when I saw the trigger warning outside the room. Otherwise absolutely perfect, just the cringy preachy undertone ruined it for me personally
Very curious the fact of being able to touch and be able to lift a real gold bar!!!
Interesting FREE museum
Lifting a gold bullion was fab. Exhibition included a Slavery and the Bank. Free admission. Lots of information on the history of the bank and UK history.
Experience the weight of Ounce Gold.
Interestingly
Interesting facts about the founding of the bank of England and the transfer to the future.
Nice
Very informative, and the changing exhibits are very interesting.
You can see real gold bars here
Interesting history of money and finance.
Small but perfectly formed. One for the adults more than kids, there's exhibits I've not seen anywhere else
It was a fascinating visit with items of interest for all ages
The children really enjoyed it
Slavery exhibition fails to mention that this was a global trade involving many countries and not the sole preserve of the UK

The Museum makes some topics very simple so everyone is able to understand. Visit highly recommended for whoever is interested in getting some knowledge regarding how and why the bank was born, what does today and the role that plays in the UK and worldwide economy. It's also a family activity, loads of children were visiting the museum too with their parents.

Although the museum is quite small, i appreciated that they were holding an exhibition on how the bank benefitted from slavery. Slavery and the History of it is a topic that we are greatly misinformed about, and it's nice seeing some efforts made to educate.
Interesting.Seems to be what the present right wing government would call "woke", as there was a display of the bank's relationship with slavery.

Free museum about the history and how the Bank of England operates. Took the kids here for half term, they got a BoE pen prize for completing age-tailored info sheets and some safe cracking. Allow about an hour to visit. Thought it might be heavy going but, surprisingly, they really enjoyed it!
Small museum, free to enter, with many interesting facts. You can also appreciate the architecture of the place. They give you the chance to hold a gold bar, something unusual and fun.
You can have seen it once
Small but interesting things to see and do.
Small but very pretty, you can touch a gold bar
Very interesting and well layed out exhibits.

A small free museum showing how the foundations of the banking system in England were created. If you want to know "how it all works" and what the future of money is, this is a must-read. Sightseeing max 1 hour. There is a souvenir shop on site.
Nice place to get out with kids. They have some activities for them and on the end there is some presents for kids. Recommend to visit if you want to see 13 kg of gold. 🪙
Haven't completed this museum - so much to take in I concentrated on the section at the back, including slavery, history and the chance to hold a real gold bar!
A short and informative tour about the Bank of England and how money was made throughout the years. Admission is free and there is no need to purchase tickets beforehand.
A short but informative self guides tour. Free admission. No need for tickets.

A small, fabulous museum located in the Square mile! I had to do a quick security check after going through the front door and that’s all. Its prominent role in Britain's trading history is something that makes me fascinated about. The bank is founded from 1694. When I came in, the 1st thing that caught my eye was the inflation rate balance game. How to keep the inflation rate is only 2% is quite challenging. Then, I got to touch the stunning 13kg pure gold bar, and I couldn’t lift it haha. Definitely worth visiting! 🙂🙂🙂

Surprisingly this came up as a kid-friendly museum and given the current inflation/recession/cost-of-living crisis it seemed worth a try. It’s not big, but is worth an hour and in the bank proper. One display says you are standing ontop of the actual gold bars which makes it all feel real. It starts with a strong ‘steer the ship’ metaphor around inflation, with several interactive displays. And good luck with the safe - finding the code to unlock it is the easy bit! There’s a nice gold bar pin as a prize if you do. Some is a little confusing, eg. the first hall mentions inflation but you have to search for a panel on the outside of the ship to find a definition. The ‘keep it within 2%’ boat video with winch and buttons for quantitative easing feels like it was borrowed from the Greenwich maritime museum and renamed without enough thought - ie. you miss the point. Slavery is a big feature and well acknowledged as the source of much of the wealth accumulated. And there’s a good amount of history without being “here are portraits of our esteemed Governors.” Being able to touch and try to lift a gold bar is fun, as are seeing the old trunk safes. A little more on how money is made (video) would help bring it to life but you can see the dies and various ways of making money. The entrance is a little odd with heavy doors and you have to double-check whether you go via security or just round the bar. A bag scanner and metal detector take a few seconds. Reception is friendly though with age-appropriate activity packs for the kids. A few things could be improved like: considering displays being easier to reach for smaller kids (edge of the first hall, little model, etc); it seems like some steps in the modern banking section could be removed; and it has an overall vibe of bankers built the architecture into which a museum was squeezed (lots of potential on the first room). Definitely worth an hour with kids 8+ and take the offered questions to slow you down and appreciate it more. Whether you’ll be any better at the monetary policy gamble at the end of it is anyone’s guess ;)

While millions of people around the world are experiencing the devastating impacts of the climate crisis, the Bank of England are still propping up the fossil fuel industry. As the referee of the UK financial sector, the Bank of England has a moral obligation to cut off the flow of finance to climate-wrecking fossil fuels projects around the world. The Bank of England Museum is free, interesting and informative; yet, many Londoners have not been here yet; I would highly recommend to anyone either local or visiting to visit it as it is only 10 min walk from St. Paul's Cathedral.

A Little Story of Origin In 1694, in London, on the street of Trudney, a beautiful building appeared, where a mechanism should be launched to successfully raise money. This was the Bank of England, whose building was designed by the Scottish William Patterson and whose first manager was Sir John Hubbell. In order to trace the history of the Bank of England, in 1988, in one of the halls of Soon, according to the queen's wish, a specially designed museum was created. The museum is open to visitors only on weekdays, so for weekends you can visit other free museums. Halls are very spacious and large, no windows on the walls, light comes only from the round glass dome on the ceiling. In the museum you have the opportunity to touch and feel the weight of a real gold bull with a purity of 99%, I think its weight is about 13kg, it is in a special transparent camera under 24/7 video surveillance and security, you have some power to make it lift up :). Have a nice visit to the treasury of the bank!

An amazing place and a terrific experience. I never fail to be enthralled whenever I visit this free London treasure. Here’s the history of money and finance presented in easily digestible soundbites with lots to do and engage children and young visitors. The Bank has a fascinating history to show and share and it is beautifully presented with wide and easy access for wheelchairs and plenty of sitting space for tired visitors. And there’s free WiFi too. The good and great came here - Dickens, T S Eliot, George Eliot ... And the bad too - fraudsters, swindlers and thieves aplenty!!! But the best bit is ... you get to hold a real gold bar and lift it (and boy, is it heavy!!) And you get to understand finance and how it works. It is an experience to treasure and takes about 1.5 hours to do it thoroughly and properly. Do go - you’ll be amazed, fascinated and enthralled.

On a visit to the City of London, I went past the Bank of England, and seeing the Museum, could not resist going in. Entry is free, and the museum is big enough, with enough information and exhibits, to spend a good couple of hours here. You will need to go through an x-ray machine and you are not allowed to take photo's. When making enquiries I was told I could handle a gold-bar. However please do not get too excited. You will not be able to wave it about over your head. (It is in a glass box, a bit like a hazardous items device from an epidemic film, though without the gloves). It should be said that security is at a level, where you cannot take down the bank, not slip any items into your pocket. Museum tells the history of the Bank of England, as well as the architecture. There are displays of coins, notes and bullion and you will be able to handle, rather awkwardly, with one hand, a gold bar. The bars are heavy, if I were to lift them, as a bank-worker, I would do it with two hands. The history of the Bank, and of notes of exchange, coins and notes, from the very start, right up to the present, is all set out. All but the youngest will remember some events; be it Gordon Brown making the bank independent, or the introduction of decimalization a generation earlier. I visited 1/5/13, so just over a week before this review. A visit to this Museum is recommended.
